 <Header id="B">
  <h1>Pointer Arithmetic &amp; Arrays</h1>
 </Header><div>
  <p class="firstLine">
   You can <strong>change the location</strong> where a pointer points by incrementing
   or decrementing it. You can also
   <strong>generate new pointer</strong> values by adding or subtracting integers
   from an existing pointer. The <mark>effective address</mark> depends upon the
   <strong>base type</strong>
   of the pointer.
  </p>
  <p>
   Given <tt>4</tt>-byte <tt>int</tt> and <tt>8</tt>-byte
   <tt>double</tt>, if you add <tt>1</tt> to an integer address, the new address
   produced is <tt>4</tt> bytes larger than the original pointer value; if you add
   <tt>1</tt> to a <tt>double</tt> address, the new address is <tt>8</tt> bytes larger.
  </p>
  <pre
   class="language-cpp"><code>int array[] = &lbrace;1, 2, 3, 4, 5&rbrace;;
int *p = array;     // p &lt;- &amp;array[0]
p = array + 1;      // p &lt;- &amp;array[1]
p = array + 4;      // p &lt;- &amp;array[4]</code></pre>

  <p>
   Of course, unlike a pointer, you
   <mark>cannot increment or decrement</mark> an array name.
  </p>
